ription":"Configure small budget and wire classifier to a fake client. Verify oversized input is truncated or rejected per policy and that dispatch behavior matches policy (sent only when allowed).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Provider-reported token usage for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Needs real provider-reported usage over real HTTP/API contract; mocks can trivially pass and hide tokenizer/accounting mismatches. Agentic was considered, but behavior text targets usage accounting, not quality of model decisions/output content, so System is the tighter failure boundary.","test_description":"Execute real API calls for representative documents, read provider usage metadata from responses, and assert reported input/total tokens do not exceed configured budget.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Cannot be reduced to Integration without losing the real provider accounting failure mode.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.06,"System":0.62,"Agentic":0.29,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is retry orchestration across classifier + API client + backoff/timer logic. In-process fake client returning rate-limit then success can reproduce the real failure. Real OS/network not required; model output quality not involved; no multi-step agent pipeline, so System/Agentic/Workflow are disqualified.","test_description":"Use a fake API client that returns rate-limit error first, then success. Assert module waits/backs off, retries, and returns successful classification instead of surfacing the initial error.","plan_consistent":tr